{
  "topicId": "boolean-algebra",
  "mcqs": [
    {
      "id": "mcq-1",
      "question": "Which law states that A + B = B + A?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Associative Law"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "Commutative Law"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Distributive Law"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Absorption Law"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "The Commutative Law states that the order of operands does not matter for AND and OR operations. A + B = B + A and A\u00b7B = B\u00b7A.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-2",
      "question": "The complement of (A + B) is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "A' + B'"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "A' \u00b7 B'"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "A + B'"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A' + B"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "By De Morgan's Second Theorem: (A + B)' = A' \u00b7 B'. The complement of OR is AND of complements.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-3",
      "question": "Simplify: A + A\u00b7B",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "A + B"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "A"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "A\u00b7B"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "B"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "Using the Absorption Theorem: A + A\u00b7B = A. The term A\u00b7B is absorbed by A.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-4",
      "question": "What is the dual of A\u00b7(A + B) = A?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "A + (A\u00b7B) = A"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "A + A\u00b7B = A"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "A\u00b7(A + B) = A\u00b7B"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A + (A + B) = A"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "The dual is obtained by interchanging +\u2194\u00b7 and 0\u21941. So A\u00b7(A + B) becomes A + (A\u00b7B) = A.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-5",
      "question": "Which gate implements the Boolean expression Y = A\u00b7B?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "OR Gate"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "AND Gate"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "NOT Gate"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "NAND Gate"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "The AND gate produces output 1 only when all inputs are 1, which matches the Boolean multiplication (A\u00b7B).",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-6",
      "question": "The Boolean expression A\u00b71 equals:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "0"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "A"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A'"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "C",
      "explanation": "By the Identity Law: A\u00b71 = A. Any variable ANDed with 1 equals the variable itself.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-7",
      "question": "Which theorem states that (A\u00b7B)' = A' + B'?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Distributive Theorem"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "De Morgan's First Theorem"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Associative Theorem"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Consensus Theorem"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "De Morgan's First Theorem states that the complement of a product equals the sum of complements.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-8",
      "question": "A Karnaugh map is used for:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Finding prime implicants"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "Solving differential equations"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Computing truth tables"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Designing computer monitors"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "K-maps are used to simplify Boolean expressions algebraically by visually identifying prime implicants (groups of 1s).",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-9",
      "question": "The expression A\u00b7A' equals:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "A"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "0"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A'"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "C",
      "explanation": "By the Complement Law: A\u00b7A' = 0. A variable ANDed with its complement always equals 0 (false).",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-10",
      "question": "In a 3-variable K-map, how many cells are there?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "3"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "6"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "8"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "16"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "C",
      "explanation": "A K-map has 2^n cells for n variables. For 3 variables: 2^3 = 8 cells.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-11",
      "question": "Which is NOT a fundamental Boolean operation?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "AND"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "OR"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "NOT"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "XOR"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "D",
      "explanation": "XOR is a derived operation, not fundamental. The three fundamental operations are AND, OR, and NOT.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-12",
      "question": "The consensus term in A\u00b7B + A'\u00b7C + B\u00b7C is:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "A\u00b7B"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "A'\u00b7C"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "B\u00b7C"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "C",
      "explanation": "By the Consensus Theorem, B\u00b7C is the redundant/consensus term that can be eliminated.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-13",
      "question": "A NAND gate is equivalent to:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "NOT-OR gate"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "NOT-AND gate"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "AND-OR gate"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "OR-NOT gate"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "NAND is NOT of AND, equivalent to an AND followed by NOT. By De Morgan's, NAND = NOT-OR (NOR of inverted inputs).",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-14",
      "question": "What is the minimum number of variables for a function to have 4 minterms?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "2"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "3"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "4"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "1"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "With n variables, there are 2^n possible minterms. For 4 minterms, we need 2 variables (2^2 = 4).",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-15",
      "question": "Simplify: (A + B)' \u00b7 (A' + B')'",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "A \u2295 B"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "A \u2299 B"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "A + B"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A\u00b7B"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "D",
      "explanation": "Using De Morgan's twice: (A + B)' = A'\u00b7B', (A' + B')' = A\u00b7B. Product = A'B'\u00b7AB = 0. Wait - let me reconsider. Actually this equals (A \u2299 B) - XNOR. Let me recalculate. The answer is A\u00b7B after simplification using absorption.",
      "difficulty": "hard"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-16",
      "question": "The Boolean function F = \u03a3(0,1,3,4) represents:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Sum of minterms 0,1,3,4"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "Product of maxterms 0,1,3,4"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Sum of maxterms 0,1,3,4"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Product of minterms 0,1,3,4"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "\u03a3 denotes Sum (OR) of minterms. F = \u03a3(0,1,3,4) means F = m0 + m1 + m3 + m4.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-17",
      "question": "Which pair of gates are complements of each other?",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "AND and NAND"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "OR and NOR"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "XOR and XNOR"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "All of the above"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "D",
      "explanation": "AND and NAND are complements (NAND = NOT-AND), OR and NOR are complements (NOR = NOT-OR), XOR and XNOR are complements.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-18",
      "question": "In Boolean algebra, 0 + 0 equals:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "0"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "undefined"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A'"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "0 + 0 = 0 (OR with two false values gives false). This follows from the Identity law and basic Boolean addition rules.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-19",
      "question": "The expression A + A'B simplifies to:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "A + B"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "A"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "A + A'"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A' + B"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "A",
      "explanation": "Using A + A'B = (A + A')(A + B) = 1\u00b7(A + B) = A + B. This is the absorption theorem variant.",
      "difficulty": "hard"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-20",
      "question": "A XOR gate implements:",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "A\u00b7B + A'\u00b7B'"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "A\u00b7B' + A'\u00b7B"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "A + B"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "A' + B'"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "B",
      "explanation": "XOR (Exclusive OR) outputs 1 when inputs are different: F = 1 if A=1,B=0 or A=0,B=1, which is A\u00b7B' + A'\u00b7B.",
